Compiling with multiple object files


-- Project structure:

            $ tree
            .
            ├── cmath.o
            ├── include
            │   ├── cmath.h
            │   └── cmult.h
            ├── main.o
            ├── prog
            └── src
                ├── cmath.c
                ├── cmult.c
                └── main.c

            2 directories, 8 files

1. Compile cmult.o objet file

            $ gcc -c ./src/cmult.c -I./include
            $ ls
            cmath.o  cmult.o  include  main.o  prog  src
                     ^~~~~~~

2. Recompile main.o to include new changes.
     Since main.c now depends on cmult.h and/or new symbols, it must be
   recompiled to reflect those changes.

            $ gcc -c ./src/main.c -I./include
            $ ls
            cmath.o  cmult.o  include  main.o  prog  src

3. Link all object files and run the program

            $ gcc main.o cmath.o cmult.o -o prog

            $ ./prog 
            add(4, 7) = 11
            mult(4, 7) = 28

NOTES:
    - Each .c file is compiled independently into a .o file
    - When a source file changes, only its corresponding .o file needs recompilation
    - The linker combines all required object files into the final executable
    - Missing object files during linking will result in "undefined reference" errors
